---
The Crownward Compact was the founding governance document for Shadowmere, establishing the
frontier march during Midgaard's Founding Generation expansion period when the eastern frontier
suffered repeated raids, caravan disappearances, and jurisdictional conflict between noble
charters and temple escorts. The Compact mandated three functions for the new march-town: guard
transit along the crossroads of military roads and farm belts, tax goods moving through the
junction, and process war dead before they reached core city districts. The founding settlement
mixed sword and ledger from its origin—gatehouses tracked names as carefully as troop numbers.
The Compact's underlying rationale was that uniform recordkeeping prevents panic and false-claim
wars: if every transit, every name, and every casualty was documented, jurisdictional conflicts
could be resolved by reference to record rather than by force. This principle worked during
the early march period. It degraded as emergency conditions—plague, ashfall, border wars—
generated record volume that exceeded the administrative capacity to maintain accuracy, and
clerks began layering corrections over corrections. The Compact's foundational logic—records
as governance—transformed into records as end in themselves, which is the origin of the Binder
Collegium's pathology.

