---
Midgaard's charter office treats the Crownward Compact as a subordinate governance document:
Shadowmere was established under Midgaard crown authority; Compact legitimacy derives from that
authority. Continuity faction: Midgaard retains residual administrative authority over Shadowmere
and successor factions, including the Binder Collegium's records and Crimson Household charter
claims. Charter review could in principle determine the legal status of all Shadowmere institutions.
Why it has not happened: charter review requires Guard Command presence (political decision both
factions defer), and review would require opening Midgaard's own sealed warrant records from the
Violet Compact period, which crossed through Shadowmere's processing infrastructure.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Neon Covenant governance treats the Crownward Compact as a case of administrative
overextension: a framework for frontier conditions never revised when conditions changed. Transit
defense became population control; goods taxation became resource extraction; war-dead processing
became the institutional infrastructure for managing the living. The Jade Magistracy identifies
the absence of sunset provisions and mandatory review clauses as the structural source of this
drift. Kowloon's own governance documents include mandatory review triggers at five-year intervals;
the design choice directly responds to the Crownward Compact failure case.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess cites the Crownward Compact as frontier mandate expansion without accountability: a document
establishing three specific functions subsequently interpreted to authorize expanding administrative
powers. Kiess's founding charter was written partly to prevent this—its provisions are specific,
include explicit exclusions of sealed-warrant authority, and require supermajority approval for
power expansion beyond named categories. The Compact's general language proved too flexible: each
function could be interpreted expansively by administrators who benefited from expansion. Kiess's
position on the Compact's current status: it authorized specific functions for a specific
administrative entity; that entity's dissolution terminates the authorization; successor claims
require fresh charter process.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's founding documentation cites the Crownward Compact in a specific context: early Violet
Compact-era authorization for population transfers through Shadowmere cited the Compact's "process
war dead" function as the legal basis for Shadowmere's role in processing displaced persons.
Classifying living displaced persons under the same administrative framework as war dead—the
rhetorical move the Garden Ledger Clerks identified—is the legal mechanism that allowed the Sealed
Names apparatus to route populations through Shadowmere without triggering welfare obligation
protocols. Processing war dead requires documentation; it does not require welfare provision.
Classifying resettled arrivals as undergoing the same process extended documentation functions
while suppressing welfare obligation. This chain of evidence is among the cleaner reconstructions
in the Garden Ledger project.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Strandline Compact was formalized during the same Fracture Era period that saw Shadowmere's
governance begin its pathological drift. The Strandline Compact's drafters were aware of the
Crownward Compact as a cautionary precedent: broad mandate language without accountability mechanisms.
The Strandline Compact's "harbor first" principle is the direct response—a constraint so fundamental
that no single bloc can override it even through emergency powers. The seventeen times the veto has
been invoked represent exactly the scenario the Crownward Compact lacked a mechanism to address:
emergency conditions generating pressure for single-institution override of shared governance.

flags MIDGAARD USHABTI
---
Ushabti jurisprudence examines the Crownward Compact as institutional authority that outlived
its granting principal—in the administrative sense that the "crown" authority invoked has been
through enough political transformation that its current relationship to Compact obligations is
genuinely unclear. The Solar Court-era design principle Ushabti carry—that law must be specific
enough to apply without a principal to interpret it—identifies the Compact's general mandate
language as structurally deficient. A document saying "guard transit" without specifying what
counts as transit, what counts as threat, and what powers are authorized for response has
effectively delegated those determinations to whoever controls the institution—not governance
but occupation in legal form.
